Here’s a small **Node.js notification snippet** that reads the manifest and posts to a Slack (or equivalent) webhook when a review window has expired.  

It’s lightweight, doesn’t touch any user data, and continues the transparency chain you’ve built:

```js
// reviewAlert.js
// Sends an alert if the manifest's next_scheduled_review date has passed.
// Safe for CI or cron use; does not process caller data.

import fs from "fs";
import fetch from "node-fetch";

const manifest = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync("manifest.json", "utf8"));
const today = new Date();
const due = new Date(manifest.next_scheduled_review);

if (today > due) {
  const message = {
    text: `⚠️  Review Due: ${manifest.tool} v${manifest.current_version}\n` +
          `Last reviewed ${manifest.last_review}; next scheduled ${manifest.next_scheduled_review}.\n` +
          `Please verify hotline listings and accessibility items today.`
  };

  // Replace with your secure webhook URL
  const SLACK_WEBHOOK = process.env.SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL;

  fetch(SLACK_WEBHOOK, {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify(message)
  })
    .then(r => console.log(`Notification sent: ${r.status}`))
    .catch(e => console.error("Notification failed:", e));
} else {
  console.log(`✅ Version ${manifest.current_version} current; next review ${manifest.next_scheduled_review}`);
}
```

You can trigger this script from your CI pipeline or a cron job (e.g., every Monday):

```bash
node reviewAlert.js
```

If the review date has passed, the webhook posts the alert to your chosen Slack channel or email service.  
It keeps surveillance of ethical transparency and hotline validation automatic while maintaining the tool’s non‑clinical nature and user‑privacy standards.
